cp01:SingleDataReferenceRefinement.TranslatedText: [ where EFFICACY='Y' and ITTV='Y' and AVISITCD='Wk24' and PARAMCD='ACTOT' ]

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.TranslatedText: Summary statistics of BASE; VAL at Week 24; and CHG at Week 24. Linear model analysis of CHG for dose response; model included randomized dose; site group; and baseline ADAS-Cog score (i.e. BASE). Used PROC GLM in SAS to produce p-value (from Type III SS for treatment dose); Independent terms in model are TRTDOSE (0 for placebo; 54 for low dose; 81 for high dose) SITEGRP (as a class variable) and BASE. Linear model analysis of CHG for pairwise treatment comparisons and adjusted means; using randomized treatment as class variable; site group as class variable; and baseline ADAS-Cog score in model. Used PROC GLM in SAS to produce LSMEANS for treatment differences and associated statistics. Independent terms in model are TRTPCD (as class variable); SITEGRP (as class variable); and BASE. Estimate statements and the statement LSMEANS TRTPCD / OM STDERR PDIFF CL were used to produce the adjusted means of the pairwise treatment differences.

Used PROC GLM in SAS to produce p-value (from Type III SS for treatment dose); Independent terms in model are TRTDOSE (0 for placebo; 54 for low dose; 81 for high dose) and SITEGRP (as a class variable). Linear model analysis of VAL performed to provide pairwise comparisons among treatment groups and adjusted means; using randomized treatment as class variable and site group as class variable in model. Used PROC GLM in SAS to produce LSMEANS for treatment differences and associated statistics. Independent terms in model are TRTPCD (as class variable) and SITEGRP (as class variable). Estimate statements and the statement LSMEANS TRTPCD / OM STDERR PDIFF CL were used to produce the adjusted means of the pairwise treatment differences

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.crt:DocumentRef: - ADAS Cog (11) -- Repeated Measures Analysis of Change from Baseline to Week 24

Description.TranslatedText: Likelihood based repeated measures analysis of ADAS-Cog(11) change from baseline at Week 24, includes LS Means at Week 24, pairwise comparisons between treatment groups - windowed values with no imputation for missing values, Efficacy population

cp01:SingleDataReferenceRefinement.TranslatedText: [ where EFFICACY='Y' and AWEEK>0 and ITTV='Y' and ITYPE ne 'LOCF' and PARAMCD='ACTOT' ]

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.TranslatedText: Adjusted means for the change from baseline at week 24 and pairwise comparisons between treatment groups at Week 24 using a repeated measures model with treatment group (as class variable); site (as class variable); time;treatment*time interaction; baseline score and baseline*time interaction terms; and an unstructured covariance matrix. SAS code used to perform repeated measures analysis: PROC MIXED DATA=EFF(WHERE=(AWEEK>0 AND ITTV='Y' AND ITYPE NE 'LOCF' AND PARAMCD='ACTOT')); CLASS USUBJID SITEGRP AWEEK TRTPN; MODEL CHG = TRTPN SITEGRP AWEEK TRTPN*AWEEK BASE BASE*AWEEK / OUTP=PRED DDFM=KR; REPEATED AWEEK / SUBJECT=USUBJID TYPE=UN; LSMEANS TRTPN / DIFF CL; RUN;

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.TranslatedText: Summary statistics of NPTOTBL and NPTOTMN. Linear model analysis of NPTOTMN for dose response; using treatment dose; site group; and baseline NPI-X score in model. Used PROC GLM in SAS to produce p-value (from Type III SS for treatment dose). Independent terms in model are TRTDOSE (0 for placebo; 54 for low dose; 81 for high dose); SITEGRP (as a class variable) and NPTOTBL. Linear model analysis of NPTOTMN for pairwise treatment comparisons and adjusted means; using randomized treatment as class variable; site group as class variable; and baseline NPI-X score in model. Used PROC GLM in SAS to produce LSMEANS for treatment differences and associated statistics. Independent terms in model are ARMCD (as class variable); SITEGRP (as class variable); and NPTOTBL. Estimate statements and the statement LSMEANS ARMCD / OM STDERR PDIFF CL were used to produce the adjusted means of the pairwise treatment differences. Because NPTOTMN is retained on every record only need to select the baseline record for the analysis.

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.crt:DocumentRef: - Frequency of Normal and Abnormal (Beyond Normal Range) Laboratory Values During Treatment

Description.TranslatedText: For each lab parameter, counts subjects based on most extreme value during treatment - categorized by whether that value is below, above, or within normal range, Safety population

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.TranslatedText: To select a single record for summary use LBTRMXFL. This flag is programmed so that the record with the flag set to 'Y' is the most extreme value for the subject. Therefore if that record is within normal range then no other visits for the subject are outside normal range. The normal range flag variable is LBNRIND.

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.crt:DocumentRef: - Frequency of Normal and Abnormal (Clinically Significant Change from Previous Observation) Laboratory Values During Treatment

Description.TranslatedText: For each lab parameter, counts subjects based on most extreme value during treatment - categorized by whether that value is below, above, or within threshold range, Safety population

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.TranslatedText: To select a single record for summary use LBPRMXFL. This flag is programmed so that the record with the flag set to 'Y' is the most extreme value for the subject with respect to difference from previous visit. Therefore if that record is normal then no other visits for the subject are abnormal. The previous visit comparison flag variable is LBPRFL.

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.crt:DocumentRef: - Shifts of Laboratory Values During Treatment; Categorized Based on Threshold Ranges

Description.TranslatedText: For each lab parameter, classifies subjects based on categorization of lab value at baseline and by most extreme value during treatment - categorized by whether that value is below, above, or within threshold range, Safety population

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.TranslatedText: To select a single record for summary use LBTRMXFL. This flag is programmed so that the record with the flag set to 'Y' is the most extreme value for the subject. Therefore if that record is within threshold range then no other visits for the subject are outside threshold range. The threshold range flag variable is LBTRFL.

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.crt:DocumentRef: - Shifts of Hy's Law Values During Treatment

Description.TranslatedText: Classifies subjects based on Hy's Law - 2 variations - For each variation, subject is classified as normal or abnormal at baseline and as normal or abnormal based on most extreme value during treatment, Safety population

cp01:SingleTextOrLink.TranslatedText: To select a single record for summary use HYMXTRFL for the transaminase elevations only and HYMXBIFL for the transaminase and bilirubin elevations. These flags are programmed so that if the record with the flag set to 'Y' is normal for Hy's Law then no other visits for the subject are abnormal for Hy's Law. The Hy's Law flag variable is HYLAWFL.
